comments.body:
@obfuscoder My original intent was to make this out of scope for the specification as the only entity that needs to understand a subject_token_type value is the Transaction Token Service. If the deployment wants to define a urn:x-example:params:oauth:token-type:email to identify a subject_token value of "foo@bar.com" then that is totally fine. I don't think this is an area where specification is required. 

I'm open to options and ways to better support use cases where transaction tokens are needing to be "minted" without any existing "access token".

One such use case could be a service that uses mTLS to unique identify a user (e.g. per user certificate) and then wants to specify that user as the subject of the transaction token. How does the requesting workload specify the "subject" (CN of the certificate?) to the Transaction Token Service?

@pdvrieze we should distinguish between access required to complete the transaction (all of which was consented to up-front on transaction initiation) and what individual workloads may be permitted to do while executing the transaction. 

For the flow you describe, trasnaction tokens can be used to downscope and perhaps even limit scope for individual workloads, but at no point should the overall scope of access be increased from that what is originally granted. 

I believe transaction tokens already support the scenario you describe, although the details of that flow would be implementation specific.

@bc-pi Is the idea here to allow for the general pattern of transaction tokens, without having to follow a specific protocol, so that we define both a framework/pattern and a interface to the transaction token service and by just following the pattern, you can claim support for transaction tokens? 

In essence something as general as "A gateway MAY generate a transaction token based on an access token that it received. If the exchange is made via an HTTP request to a remote server, it SHOULD follow RFC8693 as defined in this specification"?

Some questions that come to mind:

1. Does the absence of such an allowance limit adoption, or would it just be done in any event?
2. Are there interoperability concerns that arise from allowing the gateway to use alternatives to RFC8693

@tulshi and @gffletch - this feels like a big change in terms of scope

issues.body:
From https://github.com/oauth-wg/oauth-transaction-tokens/pull/253

@gffletch and @tulshi opened a discussion about the normative language used regarding the request_detailt and rctx claim. This was orthogonal to the original issue being adressed. to avoid having a PR open for a long time when the issue being raised is not related to the issue in the PR, this issue wass created instead. Screenshot of discussion below:

<img width="827" height="832" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/524de217-960a-4665-85fa-f2fdc65f0ad2" />

comments.body:
Regarding the discussion on this I believe there are two orthogonal discussion points:

@gffletch - you raised the question on whether the worklod idenitifier normative langugage needs to be stronger. Our latest language on authentication is that it is a MUST, sso that information has to be available. However, rctx is an optional claim, and so, any MUST (and arguably the SHOULD as well) is conditional on rctx ebing included. We may want to state that conditionality explicitly. e.g. if we decide it is a MUST, we need langugage like, "if the rctx claim is included, the workload identifier MUST be included as the req_wl claim).

@tulshi - I think the question you raise is separate from what George raised. I agree with your perspective that request_context is one of the inputs, but should not be the only input to determining rctx content. Enriching that with out-of-band information drawn from some back-end management service seems likely and plausible. If we remove the SHOULD, we may want to add langugage that suggest backend enrichment may be an option.

@tulshi are you ok if I just change the MAY to MUST?  It is still possible for multiple Txn-Token issues to use a predetermined signing key.

I can add a sentence along the lines of "The signing key MUST be discoverable via the `iss` claim".

If we say that, do we need to define that discovery mechanism? or can we just refer to OAuth AS Metadata?

@bc-pi - I was trying to be consistent with OAuth 2.1: https://www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-ietf-oauth-v2-1-13.html#name-communication-security

"When using https, TLS certificates MUST be checked according to [[RFC9110](https://www.ietf.org/archive/id/draft-ietf-oauth-v2-1-13.html#RFC9110)]."

RFC 9110 does refer to RFC6125 for cert validation...

@jsalowey I like this text. 

A use case that I know of in an email processing system is accepting inbound email. The workload needs the transaction token. The subject of the transaction token may be the email address or the GUID of the user who owns that email address.

I'm not sure in the above use case the user is being impersonated so maybe we tweak that wording?

pulls.body:
See issue #228 

In addition, the "request_context" is optional, so making it a SHOULD be included feels like maybe it is not optional. Instead the PR proposes language that says it is "RECOMMENDED".

@tulshi @gffletch - please review.

comments.body:
@tulshi, @gffletch This PR was about making it clear that the signature should be verified - the rest was formatting...

However, if we want to discuss rctx content (which is not the subject of this PR, but clearly a valid thing to discuss), perhaps we can merge this and open a separate issue and discuss request_context and tctx there instead? 

My preference is to contain the PR to the issue it was meant to address (clarifying that the signatture needs to be verified).

@tulshi - Following on from our conversation, I had a second read of this section.

1. I thinkBrian's point is valid - the paragraph is descriptive of a typical case, nnot normative or constraining.
2. As written, it describes the initial transaction token creation, so does not preclude the creation of a replacement transaction token (or other uses for creating an initial token).
